Case Study: Phishing Attack


Phishing is a type of cybercrime where attackers trick individuals into revealing sensitive information such as passwords, bank details, or OTPs by pretending to be a trusted entity.
This crime usually occurs through emails, messages, or fake websites.


A typical phishing attack happens in several steps. First, the attacker creates a fake message that appears to come from a legitimate source like a bank or popular service. 
Next, the message urges the victim to take immediate action, such as “verify your account” or “update your payment details.”


It usually contains a link that redirects the user to a fake website designed to look identical to the original.
When the victim enters their login credentials or financial information, the attacker captures the data. Finally, the stolen information is used for unauthorized transactions or identity misuse.


Phishing commonly targets students, working professionals, and elderly individuals who may not be aware of such scams. People who frequently use online banking or digital payments are especially vulnerable.
The consequences of phishing can be severe. Victims may lose money, have their accounts hacked, or suffer identity theft. In some cases, it can also lead to emotional stress and loss of trust in digital platforms.
This case highlights the importance of digital awareness, verifying links, and never sharing sensitive information online.
